<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=103360606936143></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f103360606936143><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=103360606936143>RE: NeW</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=103360606936143#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=67802><span id= >Plingeling</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>13 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Oct 2nd 9:04 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>If you are going to play your bard to lvl 60 you are better off putting most (or all) points in STA at creation. If you have any over put them in DEX. This will make it harder on lvl 1-50 but at 51 you will notice a lot of gear have STR and CHA and with some buffs you will hit 255 in STR easily. But STA equals HP and in the highest levels high HP is everything.<br><br>The highest mob a bard can mess is lvl 51, and if you are 60 (9 levels higher than mob) CHA importance on charm is next to none.<br><br>If you are only a casual player, put starting points in STR (carry more), DEX (less missed notes), and STA (less fatigue)<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
